# Drizzle Migration Safety

## ZERO DISCRETION POLICY

Never issue `./make.ps1 db-upgrade` without completing the full checklist below.
No exceptions - not for "simple" migrations, not for dev databases, not for empty tables.

## Known drizzle-kit bugs

### Column rename - INSERT SELECT uses wrong column names

When drizzle-kit generates a migration for a column rename via table recreation,
it uses the NEW column name on the SELECT side:

```sql
-- WRONG (what drizzle-kit generates):
INSERT INTO __new_table(new_col) SELECT new_col FROM old_table;

-- CORRECT (what it must be):
INSERT INTO __new_table(new_col) SELECT old_col FROM old_table;
```

This fails with "no such column" at runtime. The SELECT side must reference OLD column names.

### Preferred fix: skip table recreation entirely

For a pure column rename, drizzle-kit generates 8+ lines of table recreation.
The correct approach is one line - write it manually and skip drizzle-kit generate:

```sql
ALTER TABLE deliverables RENAME COLUMN group_id TO subproject_id;
```

SQLite has supported `ALTER TABLE RENAME COLUMN` since 3.25.0.

## Two migration paths - know which one applies

### Path 1 - app startup (always runs, no action needed)

`database.ts` calls `migrate()` on every startup. It reads `migrations/` and
applies any unapplied migrations to the Electron database automatically.
Use this for normal development - just restart the app after generating a migration.

### Path 2 - db-upgrade (for pre-applying to a live database)

`./make.ps1 db-upgrade` runs drizzle-kit migrate against the same AppData database.
Use this only when you need to apply a migration WITHOUT restarting the app,
or to verify the migration runs correctly before the app starts.

The app startup path is sufficient for all normal development.

## When to reset migrations entirely (dev only)

If the schema has diverged significantly and the database has no important data:

1. Delete the database file
2. Delete all `.sql` files and `.json` snapshots in `migrations/`
3. Reset `migrations/meta/_journal.json` to `{"version":"7","dialect":"sqlite","entries":[]}`
4. Run `./make.ps1 migration` - generates one clean migration from current schema
5. Start the app - it auto-migrates on first startup

## Mandatory checklist before every db-upgrade on a live database with data

- [ ] Read the generated .sql file in full
- [ ] For every INSERT SELECT: verify SELECT side uses OLD column names
- [ ] For every new NOT NULL column with no old equivalent: confirm table is empty,
      or provide a valid default in the SELECT
- [ ] Back up the database:
      `Copy-Item "$env:LOCALAPPDATA\Politicket\data\politicket.db" "$env:LOCALAPPDATA\Politicket\data\politicket.db.bak"`
- [ ] Run `./make.ps1 db-upgrade`
- [ ] If it fails: `Copy-Item "...\politicket.db.bak" "...\politicket.db"` to restore

## Safe vs unsafe operations

Safe (drizzle-kit handles correctly):
- Add a nullable column
- Add a table
- Drop a column
- Drop a table
- Rename a table (ALTER TABLE RENAME)

Unsafe (require manual SQL or manual review):
- Rename a column - use `ALTER TABLE t RENAME COLUMN old TO new` directly
- Add a NOT NULL column to a table with existing rows - needs a default

## Rollback

drizzle-kit has no downgrade. The only rollback is restoring from backup.
